    "Physics Constraints": "The incompressible Navier–Stokes equations are applied: ∂u/∂t + u·∇u = -∇p + ν∇²u, ∇·u = 0. Known boundary conditions and initial conditions are enforced at available locations/times. Where boundary/initial data are missing, no explicit constraint is applied, but the PDE residual is minimized there. The constant kinematic viscosity ν is assumed given; if unknown, it would require an additional inference step. Incompressibility is enforced as a soft penalty via the continuity residual; no other holonomic constraints are imposed.",
    "Model Choice": "A physics-informed neural network (PINN) with fully connected layers maps (x, y, t) to (u, v, p). This choice directly accommodates sparse data, physical PDE residuals computed via automatic differentiation, and soft enforcement of constraints. An alternative streamfunction formulation would enforce ∇·u=0 by construction, but complicates fitting to velocity data and boundary conditions, especially under partial information. The penalty approach is chosen for its flexibility and straightforward integration of data and physics. It requires careful monitoring of divergence drift.",
    "Training Strategy": "Loss comprises: (i) data misfit (MSE on u, v at observed points); (ii) PDE residuals (momentum and continuity) at collocation points (dense random sampling inside the domain and along boundaries/initial time); (iii) boundary and initial condition residuals where data are available; (iv) pressure regularizer (e.g., zero mean or L2 penalty) to break the pressure shift degeneracy. Continuity loss weight is adaptively adjusted: if the maximum |∇·u| on a validation set exceeds a threshold (e.g., 1e-3 times a characteristic velocity scale), the weight is increased. Optimization uses Adam with learning rate decay; loss terms may be balanced via gradient statistics or fixed weights after hyperparameter tuning. Early stopping is based on a validation metric combining velocity error and divergence magnitude. Missing BC/IC are treated as inferrable, with L2 regularization on network parameters to prevent overfitting.",
